    "narrative": "The offensive ceiling for Ghost Ride the WHIP centers on the favorable matchup against Schultz, elevating both **Max Muncy** (68.95) and **Tyler Soderstrom** (72.83) into high-impact territory. While **Tyler Soderstrom** carries the higher efficiency score due to his middle-of-the-order positioning, both players benefit from a +19% bump stemming from the SP\u2019s poor projected command. The standout play, however, remains **Mickey Moniak** (75.75). A rare combination of a friendly park, a favorable right-handed platoon matchup against Sasaki, and a prime #2 hole placement makes him the cornerstone of today\u2019s production. Despite a high-caliber arm in Gausman, **Corbin Carroll** remains an essential start (72.32); his dual-threat potential against a top-tier pitcher provides the necessary floor for a roster that prioritizes stolen bases as its lifeblood.\n\nWe continue to monitor the risks associated with the bottom of the order, specifically **Austin Riley** (55.79), whose efficiency is suppressed by the matchup against Painter. The most difficult bench decision involved **Alex Freeland**, whose score of 53.65 pushed him to the edge of the active roster. Ultimately, **Alex Freeland** was squeezed out because his #9 batting position creates a significant drag on counting stats compared to the higher-upside profiles of **Max Muncy** and **Tyler Soderstrom**. Meanwhile, **Vinnie Pasquantino** (53.63) remains a marginal start today; his raw talent is significant, but the steep penalty for the dynamic platoon disadvantage against the lefty Weathers limits his projected output. Owners should exercise caution with the lineup pending for **Corbin Carroll**, **Max Muncy**, **Tyler Soderstrom**, and **Austin Riley**; any defensive adjustments that push these hitters into the bottom third of the order could necessitate a re-evaluation of their daily efficiency scores.",
